==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Cotter
<hw>Cot"ter</hw> <pr>(k⟦ocr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A piece of wood or metal, commonly wedge-shaped, used for fastening
together parts of a machine or structure. It is driven into an opening
through one or all of the parts. <note>[See <xex>Illust.</xex>]</note>
In the United States a cotter is commonly called a
<altname>key</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A toggle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cotter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Cotter
<hw>Cot"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To fasten with a
cotter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cottidae</ent>⟦br⟧
